postcontent:
Selling my very rare Gen 3 Patriot Ordnance Factory piston-driven np3 coated upper with a 7.25" fluted match-grade barrel perfect for the ultimate pistol or SBR (short barrel upper) build. Less than 2 mags have been fired thru her. Upper receiver, BCG, gas plug, and charging handle are all coated in POF proprietary np3 finish which is super slick, resulting in very little wear to moving parts, excellent lubrication qualities for use with or without gun oil, and can be cleaned with the wipe of a rag, no solvents needed. Best finish in the industry! Upper features a factory removable 4 prong flash hider, POF proprietary monolithic quad rail w/ included sling mount, and piston system which keeps the upper running much cleaner and cooler than standard low-end direct impingement ARs. These are the highest quality, most reliable, and most accurate AR uppers on the planet and very rare with the 7.25" barrel. Don't miss out on this opportunity, only see a couple of these a year go up for sale in the US. These uppers retail for almost $1700, if you can even find one. My loss is your gain! If a face to face meet isn't feasible, this can be shipped right to your door, no FFL necessary. Shipping is $30 within CONUS and I can accept a credit card payment thru a discreet Paypal transaction. Know your local, state, and NFA laws regarding SBRs.

Technical specs:
Barrel
• 7.25"
• Match grade barrels fluted to reduce weight and dissipate heat.
• 4150 Mil-B-11595E chromoly alloy.
• Corrosion resistant nitride heat-treated 1:10.
• POF-USA 4 prong muzzle devices.
• POF-USA oversized heat-sink barrel nut.
• 5.56x45 mm NATO (.223 Remington) chamber.

Method of Operation
• Semi-auto (P415) or full-auto select-fire (P416) rotating bolt, short-stroke gas piston system.
• Corrosion resistant nitride heat-treated gas piston system consisting of a single piece gas block, gas plug, gas piston, and operating rod.
• Multi-position regulating gas system with normal, suppressed, and bolt-action (off) operating modes.

Bolt & Carrier
• Nickel plated bolt carrier with integrated bolt carrier key.
• POF-USA roller cam pin with chrome plated stem and NP3 roller.
• Chrome plated bolt.
Upper Receiver
• POF-USA patented Modular Railed Receiver™ (M.R.R.™); free-floating monolithic rail system.
• CNC machined 7075-T6 aircraft aluminum alloy.
• 2-piece upper receiver.
• NP3 billet charging handle.

Handguard
• POF-USA free-floating modular, aluminum handguard.
• Two 5-slot and one 12-slot modular rail sections for bottom, sides, or top of "M" Rail (14" and 16" barrels only).
• Integrated picatinny rail-estate for 10" and 7.25" barrels.
• Available in black anodized and olive drab or burnt bronze Cerakote (match to receivers). Black anodized for NP3 receivers.

Weights
• 5.1 lbs. (empty)

Manufacturing
• All raw materials, heat-treats, platings/coatings, accessories, and component parts on our weapon systems are made 100% through U.S. owned and operated steel mills and manufacturers.

• Why doesn’t POF offer chrome lined barrels?
All of our barrels are Case Harden Nitrate Heat-Treated to 70 RC.  The steel case is softer than our chambers. Our case hardened barrels shoot consistently better groups on all of our weapon systems then chrome lined barrels. Our barrels are easier to clean and don’t copper foul like chrome lined barrels. Our case hardened nitrate heat treated barrels are 10x’s thicker in the hardness area of the barrel (case hardness .005” thk., chrome lined .0005” thk.).  Chrome lining can delaminate (peel away from barrel surface) from heat, and the chrome lining doesn’t plate evenly on the entire surface of the bore and grooves.

• What is the normal-use barrel life of the POF barrels?
You can expect to get at least 20,000 plus rounds out of our Nitrate heat-treated case hardened barrels. All of our barrels are over 2x’s harder than MIL-SPEC  and hammer forged barrels. We know of a few weapons that have 40,000 plus rounds through them, and still no need to replace the barrel.

• What is the recommended break-in procedure for my POF barrels?
There is no break-in required. When you first get your weapon clean the barrel properly using proper cleaning equipment prior to shooting. After shooting properly clean the barrel using proper cleaning equipment. The barrels are case-hardened Nitrate heat-treated to 70 RC. All of our barrels are over 2x’s harder than stainless steel, MIL-SPEC and hammer-forged barrels, and 10x’s more corrosion resistant.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester 1885 'Winder musket' Rifle PRICE REDUCED AGAIN
postcontent:
Winchester 1885 'Winder musket' Rifle in 22 short.

TOOK it to Cabela's for evaluation. They have one there in a little better condition for $1500. Based on their evaluation I am dropping the price to a more realistic amount remembering a have 40 of the rare rounds to go with. $700

Stock Configuration & Condition: The stock is original condition and original finish wood. The wood to metal fit is proud at the tangs which would allow for refinish. There is darkening of the wood. There are scattered marks and depressions, there are a couple of cracks. This is good for an old Winchester.
Type of Finish: Blue & Case Color Hardened Finish Originality: Factory Original.
The bore is almost bright and the rifling is a bit worn. 
This rifle retains about 60% of its Factory Original metal finish. The balance of the finish shows thinning on the barrel edges and a general light drift to patina. The frame shows a bit more thinning of the finish, with some muted case colors. There is a screw missing. The markings are crisp. Overall, this rifle rates in about good condition.

I have fired the rifle and it is quieter than my air rifle. Although this one is chambered for 22 short (I have 40 rounds left which I will include), it will receive a 22 LR. Some of these where chambered/stamped for 22 LR.

I would consider an interesting trade plus cash to equal the asking price.  Thanks for looking. I have other photos on serious request.

Wiki history: The Winder musket was the brainchild of Colonel C. B. Winder, who advocated marksmanship training with a rifle of similar size and weight to a service rifle but chambered in .22 rimfire, which was both economical and suitable for indoor ranges. The Winder musket was based on the Winchester Model 1885 single shot rifle.

Although it was never officially referred to as the Winder musket, the weapon was informally named in honor of Colonel C. B. Winder, and has since generally been referred to as the Winder musket.
Winder muskets were used for target and training purposes well into the early Twentieth Century. Many were purchased by the United States Ordnance and many were issued to American N.R.A. affiliated rifle clubs. The Winder musket was superseded by the 1922 Model bolt-action training rifle, and remaining Winder muskets were sold.
